an><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">South West, appearing on BBC World News, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Newshour</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, Radio one</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and 5-Live to name but a few outlets. Along with providing information about the ear</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">thquake they also explained the challenges of providing rescue and relief in a region beset with separatist and sectarian violence. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The year saw strong work from the African teams. The </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mali</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> crisis became a major international story and BBC Africa set up a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> dedicated Mali desk to co-ordinate and to enrich coverage. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Newsday’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> coverage of the breaking news of the death of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Ethiopian</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> PM, Meles Zenawi, included a number of high profile interviews which were picked up by other international news organisations.  BB</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">C Africa also carried extensive coverage of the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Zimbabwe</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> election, and the Westgate shopping mall attack in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Kenya</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, and shared their expertise across BBC networks.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WS English</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> launched a new</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> schedule including the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> morning radio programme, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Newsday</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, replacing its long lasting news strand </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">World Today</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. The programme, jointly presented from London and Johannesburg, targeted Anglophone audiences in Sub Saharan Africa offering them key global stories, African perspective and insights enriching their dail</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">y diet of news with a broader agenda. Slightly more informal in tone, the programme built on key BBC values</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. Initial research showed that </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">global audiences, and especially African ones, liked the show for its tone and informality, and that it provided relev</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ant news to both African and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">lobal audiences.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC WS covered sensitive stories with authority and from a wide variety of perspectives. It offered an open platform for discussion and adequate context for stories such as the Delhi gang rape which triggered </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">unprecedented outpouring of anger across </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">India</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and the Bo Xilai verdict in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">China</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> when the Chinese Service kept its audiences abreast of the court proceedings through its website and online forum.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC Media Action and BBC World Service worked together on a number of programmes across Asia, Africa and the Middle East. For example, in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Afghanistan</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, BBC Media Action and the BBC Afghan Service have been working together to produce </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Open Jirga (Assembly)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Kenya</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, BBC Media Action and BBC Swahili have worked together to produce the weekly debate show </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sema Kenya (Kenya Speaks).</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">TV and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">digital</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> developments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The challenges in reaching global audiences are intensifying. Global state funded and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">commercial players are investing (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the BBC</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> estimate</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> CCTV’s funding has increased by $2bn per annum, and competitors including CNN and New York Times have a growing multi-lingual portfolio). At a local and regional level, news provision is </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rapidly increasin</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">g; Afghanistan, for example, now has 80 terrestrial TV stations and over 175 radio stations. Digital developments are accelerating this change. Short</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">wave listening continues to decline, with some of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC WS’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> largest audiences in Nigeria and Burma</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> facing p</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ressure. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">For the time being, radio is still </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">orld </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ervice</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> largest platform and the most cost-effective form of distribution, but as short</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">wave becomes less relevant to most audiences, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the BBC must offer</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a greater multiplatform presence.  </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Investment</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in new TV programming</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and digital output is a key part of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">World Service</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> strategy. Four new language TV bulletins were launched this year, and are now on air:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Focus on Africa: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Launched on both BBC W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">orld News and on 11 partner TV s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">tations in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">eight</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> countries. This programme is an extension of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC Africa’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> strong radio brand into television and represents </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">unique partnership with </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC World News. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Reporting expertise is provided by existing BBC Africa reporters in Africa, complimented by the poo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">l of N</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ewsgathering staff on the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">continent. This </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">was </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the first stage in Global News’ investment in new content and programming aimed at reaching different audiences around the world who are changing the way they consume their news. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Diira Ya Dunia: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Launched in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">August, a 30 minute bulletin aimed at Swahili speaking audiences in East and Central Africa, which airs in Tanzania and Kenya on partner TV stations.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> A</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> number of</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> new partners in DRC and Rwanda </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">have been added </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">enabling BBC WS to expand its reach in Africa.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Global India: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A weekly 30-minute magazine-style show from the Hindi service launched in November on five Hindi news channels on the ETV network in India, at prime time. Each programme gets three playouts on all five channels.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Sairbeen (Panorama): </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A th</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rice weekly one-hour TV programme from the Urdu service of regional and global news for audiences in Pakistan launched in February 2013. The programme was increased to five times a week in the run up to Pakistani elections.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Although audience performance d</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ata</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> is not yet available</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, several of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> TV partners have signed-up to the programmes for another year on the same or improved commercial terms. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Feedback from Star TV on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Diira Ya Dunia</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> has been especially positive, with the CEO keen to renew the contract. In addition, in Kenya reaction on social media to editions of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Focus On Africa</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Diira Ya Dunia</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">has been extensive </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and very positive.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">World Service Digital</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This year, the last seven</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">language </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">websites </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">were</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> updated in accordance with the new and improved visual and presentation style, in line with the ‘feel and look’ of the rest of the BBC sites. 11 Nokia Apps, 5 iOS Apps, and 4 Andr</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">oid apps have now been released</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Several World Service websites have now been converted to responsive design including Indonesia, Hausa, Arabic, Vietnamese, Turkish¸ Russian, Hindi, Afrique, Mundo, Brasil and Persian with the conversion of many more languages in progress. Responsive desig</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">n is a technology that optimises the mobile browser according to the device used – adjusting the layout to the screen size and connectivity. It is especially helpful for the language services, given the diverse markets they serve and the huge array of diff</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">erent phones and technical standards in those markets. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">As mentioned in the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Audience Figures</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> section, these developments have contributed to a 16% increase in World Service digital audience globally.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Media freedom </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">update</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Media freedom issues continue </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to affect the BBC’s ability to reach its audiences.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Many of these issues were </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">described in detail</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in BBC World Service’s written evidence submitted to the FAC’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s Human Rights inquiry.  This is a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> brief summary of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">issues </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC WS </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">has faced </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">this year</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Journalists</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">afety:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The BBC has been extremely concerned about the safety of its journalists in several parts of the world. Syria has continued to be a dangerous place to report and violence and pressures on media in Egypt have made it a difficult place t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">o work as a journalist. BBC reporter </span><span style="color:#272727; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Mohammed Moalimu, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">came close to death in Somalia when in July an al-Shabab suicide bomber detonated his explosives just as Moalimu was driving past.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> He was wounded by shrapnel in his shoulder.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">But it is not just in c</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">onflict zones that journalists’ safety is being threatened. A BBC Tamil reporter, Ponnaiah Manikavasagam, was questioned for hours by anti-terrorist police in Sri Lanka over his phone conversations with two Tamil prisoners. He was not allowed a lawyer duri</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ng the interview. BBC WS raised its concern and expressed confidence that all his activities were carried out in pursuit of normal journalistic duties. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In Turkey, during Gezi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Park protests, Turkish authorities launched a campaign of intimidation against BBC Turkish reporter, Selin Girit. She had been deployed to Istanbul to cover the protests both for Turkish and English outlets. The mayor of Ankara launched a campaign against</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Selin on Twitter, resulting in a large number of threatening messages being sent to her. In a statement, the BBC called on the Turkish </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">authorities not to intimidate its reporter and to use the established procedures if they have any complaints about BBC o</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">utput. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In Iran, security authorities have continued harassing BBC Persian staff and their families. In the weeks leading to the Iranian presidential election in June, the incidents of harassment increased and the media campaign against BBC Persian staff</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> intensified. Although after the election the harassment stopped for a while, in recent weeks a new wave of intimidation of families has started again. Families of several members of staff have been threatened to stop their relatives working for the BBC. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">To highlight the importance of journalists’ safety and the issue of impunity, the BBC is organising a conference next year. It is a follow-up to the conference it co-hosted last October. The conference will bring together senior journalists, NGOs and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">representatives from UN’s relevant bodies and governments</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> It will examine what international legal bodies could do to prosecute those who are responsible for attacking and intimidating journalists.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Jamming in China:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The jamming of BBC English short wa</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ve services by China has occurred since February this year and also affects reception of the service in many other Asian countries.  </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Access to the BBC Chinese (Mandarin) website has been completely blocked since its launch in 1999.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The BBC strongly cond</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">emns</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> this action, but</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> despite </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">representations made to the Chinese Ambassador, the regulator, and the Director Global News raising the issue in meetings duri</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ng his recent visit to China, the BBC</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> has not received a response</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> from the Chinese authorities</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Broadcasts suspended in Sri Lanka:</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC WS suspended its broadcasts on SLBC (the Sri Lankan Broadcasting Corporation) following continued interruption and interference of BBC Tamil programming.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Despite requests for discussion about any complaints that SLBC</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> might have had about any specific output, the issue has not been resolved.  The BBC took similar action in 2009 when its services were also disrupted.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Audiences in Sri Lanka can continue to listen to th</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e BBC on short wave and via </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">online services</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">TV par</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">tnership suspended in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Turkey:</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Following the start of protests in Turkey in June the Turkish service took the decision to suspend its TV partnership with NTV in Turkey, after NTV interfered with its broadcasting. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC Turkish subsequently relaunched its digi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">tal offer with a greater emphasis on mobile, video and social news, and has seen its traffic soar more than 350% in one year alone with nearly 90% of the audience coming from within Turkey.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Progress in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Burma:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">There were uplifting developments in Burma</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">/Myanmar</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">where the government has </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">strictly</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> controlled  the media over a number of years. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">For the past nine months BBC Media Action has been helping the state broadcaster - MRTV - to achieve its declared aim of evolving into a public service broadcaster by </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">January 2015. As a result of this support MRTV now has its first prime-time politics programme to feature interviews with members of all the parties represented in Parliament, a new radio current affairs programmes featuring differing points of view and an</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> emerging newsgathering structure that is more independent than anything the country has known in the past few decades .</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In addition a youth programme is broadcast on the BBC's Burmese Service </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">that informs audiences about governance issues and encourages </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">discussion and participation and developing other projects to improve livelihoods, health and resilience to natural disasters. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">There have</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> been</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a number of distribution break</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">throughs with BBC TV channels including BBC World News now available on the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">SkyNet </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">TV platform in Burma</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rebroadcasting deal </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Padamyar FM</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and another one with key FM station </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Shwe</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> which covers 98% of the country in the pipeline.  In addition, t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Burmese service became the first international broadcaster on the mobile platfor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">m in Burma through the launch of daily audio bulletins, as well as SMS bulletins. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Awards</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC World Service won five awards at this year’s </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Sony Radio Academy Awards</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Witness</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> won a Gold in the in the Best Speech Programme category, Paul Woods' </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Bombardment of Homs</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> documentary also won Gold in the Best News Feature or Documentary category marking his brave and vivid reporting during the Syrian crisis, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Newshour </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">won Silver in the hugely competitive Best News and Current Affairs Programme category an</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">d the BBC also picked up Silver for the outstanding and moving </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Assignment/Crossing Continents: Uzbekistan</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, a co-production between World Service and BBC Radio 4</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> on forcible sterilisation in Uzbekistan</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Finally, BBC reporter, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Jon Donnison</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, was </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">award</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ed a Sil</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ver for Radio Journalism</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of the Year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The BBC won prestigious </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">One World Media awards</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in several categories in May. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Assignment/Crossing Continents</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">was again successful winning</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the Radio Award.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> BBC Persian’s Tahir Qadiry</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> won the New Voice Award for what the judges called ‘presenting a fresh and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">alternative take on Afghanistan’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC News correspondent, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Ian Pannell and cameraman Darren Conway </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">were</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> awarded this year’s prestigious </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">David Bloom Award</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">recognition of their r</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">eporting from the Idlib province in Syria on BBC World News America. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ater in October Ian Pannell was again recognised for his reports of the conflict in Syria, along with re</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">porter Paul Wood and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">cameramen Fred Scott and Darren Conway, when they won a prest</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">igious </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Emmy Award</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">And in the last month, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC World News</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> won a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">United Nations Association of Australia Media Award</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> for the film </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Understanding Yemen: Torture, Trauma and Al-Qaeda</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In July </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">WS’s Matt Davies, was recognised as Journalist of the Year and journalist, Fiona Graham, won an award for Best </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Information and Communication Technology</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Feature in the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Diageo Africa Business Reporting Awards</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The work of Global News Creative Services Team</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> was recognised</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">at the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Promax awards</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in LA </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in June.  </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The </span><a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/4ymwdoin1yop3sz/BBC_World_News_2m_Facebook_Fans.mp4"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">BBC World News </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Facebook</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> animated </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">infographic</span></a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">won Gold, Silver went to the BBC World Service 27 languages print campaign and Bronzes were awarded for the BBC World Service Wimbledon radio promo and BBC World Service 80th anniversary exhibition design. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transfer to the licence fee</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BBC WS is now looki</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ng ahead to more stable funding and the benefits of greater integration with BBC News, as a result of the transfer to the licence fee on 1 April 2014. It will join BBC Monitoring which has been funded by the licence fee since 1 April 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">On 25 June 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the BBC Trust published its draft Operating Licence for the World Service, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">setting out its strategy for World Service in the licence fee, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">for public consultation. Further context was provided in the accompanying Position Paper “</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">BBC World Service – A licen</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ce fee funded service</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">”.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> The Trust is currently assessing the feedback received during the consultation and will publish its responses in due course. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The draft Operating Licence defines the Objectives, Priorities and Targets (as agreed with the Foreign </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Secretary), scope of services, funding and performance measurement of the World Service under the licence fee. Any significant change to the Licence will require the approval of the BBC Trust.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Policy Position paper makes it clear that the World Servic</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">will </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">be an integral part of the BBC News operation, which provides independent and impartial news and analysis to UK and global audiences. Most importantly, the paper states that the Trust will ensure that the distinctive service offered by the World Ser</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">vice is protected, and enhanced. The impact of the World Service will not be diminished as a result of an administrative change in funding. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Trust also announced its plan to increase funding for World Service to £245m in 2014/15 (in the 2013/14 financ</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ial year the total grant from the UK Government for World Service is £238.5m). Under the terms of the Operating Licence, any planned or actual change in the licence fee-funded content and distribution budget of more than </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">10% in real value will be regarded </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">as a significant change and require approval from the BBC Trust. The Trust also proposed that in addition to its licence fee budget, World Service should seek non-licence fee sources of funding (including commercial funding) where appropriate and within re</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">gulatory requirements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">On 8 October 2013 the Director-General of the BBC shared his ambition for the BBC. Reflecting the importance and value of the World Service, the announcements included an ambition to double the BBC’s global audience by 2022 from 250</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> million users a week to 500 million.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Within the BBC Executive, the ‘1414 Programme’ has been created to ensure that all aspects of the transition of the World Service to licence fee funding are addressed. The programme is considering ways of integrating the World Service to ensure maximum val</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ue for licence fee payers and putting a future strategy in place which offers the best possible service to global audiences. The programme is also considering appropriate accountability and regulatory regimes, working with Government where necessary. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Thi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s programme is progressing to schedule. James Harding, Director News and Current Affairs, assumed the role of Executive Sponsor from September 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">22 October 2013</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Available at </span><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbctrust/news/press_releases/2013/ws_operating_licence.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.bbc.co.uk/bbctrust/news/press_releases/2013/ws_operating_licence.html</span></a></p></body></html>